headline: 'You need a lot of nerve to live here': Inside Donetsk, the final stronghold of Ukraine's defense
description: The front line is drawing closer to Kramatorsk, now de facto the region's capital. On August 22, massive shelling targeted the city's outskirts. For Kyiv, giving up the Donbas territories still under its control would mean handing over its front line of defense to the Russian army.

headline: Alberto Barbera, artistic director of the Venice Film Festival: 'We are witnessing a return to reality-based cinema'
description: The head of the selection committee for the Italian festival, whose 82nd edition runs from August 27 to September 6, told Le Monde in an interview that 'in such troubled times, films play an important role.'

headline: Will France's government collapse? Do the math with our simulator
description: To survive the confidence vote on September 8, Prime Minister François Bayrou must secure a majority of votes cast in the Assemblée Nationale. Abstentions and absences will not be counted.

Mohammed VI, a king with big foreign policy plans
description: 'The Enigma of Mohammed VI' (4/6). In recent years, the Moroccan monarch has become highly active on the international stage. From the highly sensitive issue of Western Sahara to Morocco's rapprochement with Israel, he has often established himself as the central player.

headline: Life in the West Bank settlement of Kedem Arava: 'We're not taking anyone's place, there is only sand around us'
description: Established in 2017 near the Jordanian border, the Kedem Arava settlement contains prefabricated homes housing some 60 families, former city dwellers seeking a life closer to nature. While most residents deny ideological motivation, their presence fully aligns with the annexation of Palestinian territory sought by the Israeli far right.

headline: Jacques Rancière, philosopher: 'Today, the people fueled by resentment manufactured by billionaires dominate the public sphere'
description: 'May '68 Thinkers Reflect On Trump Era' (1/6). The philosopher of emancipation examines the roots of the current reactionary offensive. He views contemporary utopian micro-communities as new ways of 'living as equals.'
